<br>
Zerlatik's Note: As many of us have left EQ in recent days to pursue other games, I thought I'd assist anyone heading out by providing some info on FFXI.  With any luck, having this as a device for comparison may also help liven up many of the old arguments about wizards in EQ, which seem to have devolved lately into shouting matches instead of any kind of constructive discussion.  Be advised that this post is rather long, you may want to read it in shifts or come back to it later after you've thought about something.  Also, when you're done, feel free to scroll back up to the top and see if you can spot your house from up here.  I welcome any discussion of the merits of each game, as well as any ideas you may want to present that might work in EQ based on what Square-Enix has done with FFXI.  I've numbered everything, and it won't hurt my feelings if you skip any sections that don't interest you.<br>
<br>
1. Release info.<br>
FFXI is scheduled for its North American, (NA from here on out), launch in Q4 of 2003 for PC and Q1 of 2004 for PS2.  Yes, it's a multi-platform launch.  Yes, players will be able to play on the same server regardless of which platform you choose to run.  The major holdup in production appears to be finding a NA distributor for the new 40MB PS2 HD.  Yes, that is a whole crapload of space for a console game, S-E took the multiplatform launch line that seriously.  Translation appears to be mostly complete at this point.  Beta testing on the NA version began a week or two ago, it's probably too late to sign up now.<br>
<br>
However, if you don't want to wait that long, (and you can read at least some Japanese), the game is out in both versions in Japan.  I will leave the logistics of the actual import process largely up to you, however <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.ffxionline.com" target="top">www.ffxionline.com</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> has a pretty decent guide to importing, which walks you through the actual setup and account creation portions of the game.  If you do import, you will need the following: a copy of the game, a Japanese language PS2 HD (only if you're using the PS2 version, and you may also need a Japanese language PS2), and possibly the Visions of Z(j/g)iraat expansion if you are interested in playing in any of the expansion zones, or questing for the expansion advanced jobs.  (Note that the NA version will ship with the expansion included, both versions, and the PS2 one will probably bundle the HD as well).  <br>
<br>
Importers will probably also need a Japanese address in order to register the product and get online.  As far as importers have seen, this addy is mainly for marketing purposes and doesn't serve any vital role unless you really dig junkmail.  Thus, some importers recommend falsifying a Japanese addy.  S-E does not seem to check the addresses beyond verifying that they could actually be in Japan.  A dummy address also has a slight advantage over using an existing addy in that you don't spam some poor homeowner or business with unwanted junkmail.  I'd visit the boards over at FFXIonline and ask one of the Japanese players to give you the addresses of the last two numbers on his street before it either dead ends or is crossed by another street.  Add or subtract 10 to this number, which should create an address in the middle of an intersection.  All junkmail thus heads to the dead-letter office, and you're now a Japanese citizen in S-E's eyes.<br>
<br>
2. Logging in and setting up.<br>
Quick plug again, if you imported make sure you check the guide over at FFXIOnline.com on the bottom left menu section, (follow the link above to the site), it'll explain it all.<br>
<br>
For the rest of us, the process will be pretty straightforward, like EQ, once you're installed and the hardware is up, you just register and create a character.  And here's where it gets really interesting...<br>
<br>
First off, you don't get to select your server in FFXI, the game randomly does it for you.  It gives preference to those servers which currently are low in population, which is kinda nice if you don't particularly care about where you end up as long as the latency is good.  Server populations are thus self-regulating, you don't end up with massively overcrowded servers or others where you can travel the entire world and not see anyone.  Thus, the constant crap we see about people plugging SZ on these boards because they want players for their side or the population's low are absent from FFXI.<br>
<br>
This does bring up a concern, however.  How do you play with friends?  S-E has solved this problem with a purchaseable game item called a WorldPass.  Each WP allows you to access 5 codes which are good for 7 days.  Getting one of those codes to a friend is up to you, but once they log on, they can enter that code and create a new character on your server.  The unused codes expire after a 7 day period, you can also only purchase one WP every 7 days.  WP pricing varies in gil (FFXI money), based on the population of the server.  If for some reason that server is low and not enough people have been randomly assigned to it, WPs will be dirt cheap.  On the other hand, if you're playing on a very popular server for some reason, WPs will cost you your firstborn.  Thus, your buddy has a vested interest in helping you out once you log on to his server, since it already cost him 1k of his hard earned cash to get you to join him.  WorldShifts and Server Transfers are not allowed at this point, and don't look to be on the drawing boards for any time in the future.  <br>
<br>
3. Will it play on my system?<br>
Short answer, if you have a PS2 and buy the game bundle, yes.  If you're the PC type, it's a little trickier.  S-E has released a benchmarking program which you can pickup <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.playonline.com/Download/FFXibench.zip" target="top">here</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.  Those on dialup, beware.  This is an 11MB download, so don't make any hard plans.  Basically, download it, unzip it, make some popcorn and cue it up.  What you want to pay attention to is the little &quot;score&quot; at the bottom right.  This is your benchmark, and it resets every time the program loops itself.  From what the FFXIOnline forums have discovered, any PC bench of over 1500 should be playable.  There's a full thread on this, with badly tranlated comments from S-E <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.ffxionline.com/forums/showthread.phps?s=b09f5536805be9ca749fa75f5e670b20&amp;threadid=4307" target="top">here</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.  To give you some idea, I have a P4 at 2.5 GHZ, an 80 GB Maxtor HD at 7200 RPM, 512 MB RAM, ATI Radeon 9000 (surprisingly, ATI edges out Nvidia slightly right now in the benchmarks), and craptastic 56kbps dialup, (not fiber optic, mind you, good ol' Tommy Edison copper wires here, speeds are slow as frozen crap).  My score was between 3900 and 4000.  Anything over 4000 is probably higher than anything the game is likely to toss your way.  If you've set up your rig to run Unreal Tournament at full resolution, you'll probably need a hardware upgrade to run this game sometime around the time Satan's feet get chilly.  Be aware that this game uses the same memory management system EQ does, so it'll take as many resources as you have available unless you tell windows to treat it differently.<br>
<br>
4. Graphics.<br>
You saw the benchmark program, right?  Well, that movie's pretty much a dumbed down version of ingame graphics.  Real graphics will probably be much better than the Tarutaru beach party blowout you just witnessed.  For one thing, probably not very noticable with those palm trees, trees actually resemble trees in FFXI.  No more of the elongated cones with spiky projections we saw as the standard in EQ.  Water also resembles water, and monsters aren't oddly formed polygon blobs.  In the first 30 seconds of play, you'll probably notice better graphics than 90% of EQ.  Early Japanese players reported spending hours just watching clouds drift by.  Character customization is a bit more limited than SoL EQ, since you don't have eye color, for instance, but the models themselves are more detailed.  From a distance, it's very easy to tell races apart.  Clothing is somewhat hit and miss, however, lot of the AF (epic quested) armor for each class is downright stunning, but there are other times when you wonder about decisions.  There's a lot more lace, ruffles, and frills than I was expecting armor to have.<br>
<br>
5. Gameplay, (A.K.A. the section you probably give an actual crap about).<br>
<br>
(a) East side v. West side.<br>
Rap music references aside, (henceforth referred to as that musical genre missing a letter 'c' at the front), there is a major difference in the feel of FFXI.  This is definitely an Eastern RPG.  You'll get the picture a little better later on, but the basic themes are pretty easy to spot.  Clothing is one area, but you'll also notice that characters have slightly larger heads, big eyes, and play tends to be focussed on party exploits and player status, rather than the endless EQ cycle of levelling and item acquisition.  How you interact with the world actually matters in FFXI.  Plus, there's the huge LOTR style cutscene that begins the game...<br>
<br>
(b) Order up!<br>
You're going to notice a big difference vs. EQ right off the bat... MENUS!  Yup, FFXI is a standard Final Fantasy game, in that menus drive most of the action.  This is fantastic for those of us who, like me, can't remember the keystrokes for their abilities or disciplines to save their lives.  Basically, if you're able to do it, it'll appear on the menu somewhere.  Menus are also grouped pretty intuitively, it'll be pretty obvious where your special attacks and spells are located.  Also, once you've targetted an enemy for destruction, your character will move into position and start hacking away without your micromanagement.  You can interrupt him to cast or order a special attack, but he can get by without you at least to a degree.  <br>
<br>
(c) Of ringtones and shells.<br>
Guilds are done differently in FFXI.  There are actual guilds in FFXI, and I'll explain them later, but guilds as we think of them are represented by Linkshells.  To start a Linkshell, you don't petition, submit a charter, gather your followers in one place, or any of the odd stuff we're used to.  Nope, you just visit a shop and buy a Linkshell.  Once you've got one and named it, you then can start cranking out LinkPearls, which you hand out to people you want to Link with.  Everyone in the link can talk with everyone else from anywhere in Vana'diel.  If someone in your link has done things that harm your Link's reputation, you can also Kick them, much like a chatroom.  The offending party does not have to be in the same zone, or even online to be Kicked, leaving no escape from judgement.  The Linkshell system does not seem to be anywhere near as complex as the new LoY Guild Management system of EQ.  On the other hand, it doesn't really need to be.  The guild aspect of EQ has been really downplayed in FFXI, to the point where you don't really need your Linkshell for much more than companionship or party recruitment, thus you aren't stuck with a bunch of morons you dislike but have to suck up to in order to complete anything.  <br>
<br>
(d) Hulk Smash!<br>
Monsters are really interesting in FFXI.  Not just because they look like the standard FF-style circus freaks, either.  For one thing, some of them are chained as far as aggro goes.  If you attack one, he'll call a few friends before charging, which gets you that monster and a group of his nearest and dearest.  Other monsters will pretty much ignore you completely as you kill something right on top of them.  Still others only 'activate' after you've done something else.  However, best thing about monsters in FFXI is that the spawn times are short.  How short?  Well, on nearly everything that isn't a Notorious Monters, (the FFXI version of uber mobs), once it goes down another one respawns somewhere else in the zone.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :omg --><img src=http://www.graffe.com/emoticons/omg.gif ALT=":omg"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   For Notorious Monsters, spawn times seem to be actually reasonable.  The longest I've heard about was a few hours tops.  Thus, no more week long camps for Vox/Naggy/Rage.  Lots of them are also single party doable.  You can even trigger lots of these spawns.  For instance, at early levels you start to accrue Beast Coins from mobs, at later levels you can hand these in for an encounter in the Burning Circle area, 100 coins can net your lvl 40 party two lvl 50 NMs to play with, or a single lvl 90 NM for your 60ish party.  The game gives you an idea of how this place works by giving players the opportunity to summon a free NM encounter during one of the missions.  <br>
<br>
(e) That's it, I'm bored.<br>
Class is handled in a new and really interesting way in FFXI.  It's a lot like 3rd Edition D&amp;D, mixed with a fair slice of 2nd Editions Dual-Classing rules.  Race in FFXI is fixed, however your job is not.  At creation, you start as one of the six main jobs: Warrior, Monk, Thief, White Mage, Black Mage, or Red Mage, (the big six).  However, you can change jobs at any time by visiting your Mog house in town.  Here's the good part, the game remembers your progress in each class, so you can switch back if you change your mind later.  Unlike EQ, if you get bored, you don't have to competely reroll, you can stay the same character, just a different job.  So, if your Monk gets sick of punching things, you can switch to White Mage and sit back and heal for a few.  <br>
<br>
At lvl 18, you gain the ability to quest for a sub job.  Think of this like dual classing.  As a sub job, you don't get the special 2 hr ability that normally accompanies that job.  Also, the max of each subjob can only be one half of whatever is currently your main job.  You can have more exp in that job, you just can't make use of it until you level up your main some more.  You level up subjobs by switching them to main job and gaining exp in that job.  You will only ever gain exp in whichever job is set as the current main.  <br>
<br>
At lvl 30, you gain the ability to quest for an advanced job.  Advanced jobs have skills that normally aren't available to the big six classes.  The basic advanced job list includes Paladins, Dark Knights, Bards, Rangers (hello tracking), and Beast Masters (here monster, monster, monster, come help daddy kill your friends).  The expansion pack adds a number of new jobs to this listing as well, which quest in the expansion areas, such as Dragon Knight (Dragoon), Summoner, Ninja, Samurai, etc.  The quests for each different job are given out in different cities.  Each quest is pretty epic in scope, but are balanced to be accomplishable without a massive guild, unlike lots of the quests in EQ.  For instance, the quest for Dragoon requires that you first dig up a dragon egg.  Quest writeups for this recommend bringing along only six picks to the area where you start digging, it's that common.  No 3 hr foraging runs and carpal tunnel inducing click fests.  From that stage, you have a series of dungeon crawls to reach terrain features and objects to power up your egg, resulting in a final battle with a dragon to finish off the quest.  But wait, you don't need to run an EQ style dragon raid where you spend weeks waiting to ambush the bugger and race other guilds to do it.  You know where the dragon is, and exactly how to trigger it.  Yup, trigger it.  You don't race another guild, you line up behind other players in the spot and wait your party's turn.  Only holdup in the quest line is however long it takes the parties in front of you to finish killing the mob so you can click on the door and be teleported into your encounter.  Best part is that if you screw up this final battle, you can rez up and redo it once you're ready for another try, instead of repeating every other step.  Also, (this'll be important later on), you don't become each job as soon as you finish the quest, it becomes a training option at the Mog House once completed.  So, you can always unlock it now, and then save it for when you really want to play as that if you aren't sure about starting over at lvl 1 now.  It is possible, though it'd probably drive you crazy and take forever, to get to max level in every single job in the game if you so desire. <br>
<br>
(f) My faithful mount, Warky.<br>
FFXI handles transportation differently than EQ.  Unlike the PoP system of teleporters or everyone's favorite game, &quot;bug your local wizard&quot;, you're pretty limited.  You've got boats, you've got airships, and you've got chocobos.  Boats and Airship travel isn't nearly as boring as EQ, however.  There are actual battles on the boats, usually as a result of someone fishing up something fun.  Also, should you complete the quest at lvl 20 for your Chocobo raising licence, you can ride one of the series famed Chocobos.  The little birds are handled differently than EQ's horses, however.  For one thing, they're rented rather than bought, (rent's cheap BTW).  You rent them at the edge of town, and they stay with you for much of the way.  They can't go into dungeons or towns, however, so you're limited in travel if you go by birdback.  Also, they tend to toss you off if they get too worn out, which can be annoying.  They also need to be fed, which brings up an interesting special feature of chocobos, they can dig.  Chocobos aren't very picky diggers, if you order one to dig somewhere, it'll turn up special items with the same regularity as it turns up food.  Location also influences what they dig up, dig next to a stream and you get water based items.  One caution however, is that Chocobos HATE fire, doesn't matter if it's player or monster based.  If they see fire, they'll toss you on your tukuss and run for it.  You also can't attack from birdback, although you can still target monsters to track them.<br>
<br>
(g) Moogles!<br>
Probably the most important feature of your gaming experience will be your Mog House.  This sucker sits in your hometown and is kinda like your own private kingdom.  It stores your items, banks your cash, allows you to rest up, helps mail things to other Mog Houses, etc.  It's one stop shopping for all your adventuring needs.  Some tradeskills also make use of the Mog House, and you can grow a number of items in your garden if you so desire.  When switching jobs in the Mog House, one caution is to make sure you unequip all the gear that can't be used in the new job before you make the switch and bank or sell it, as this gear doesn't equip over.  Also, as the name implies, the place is crawling with cute, cuddly, and thoroughly evil Moogles.<br>
<br>
(h) No, Charlie, they don't float.  Now get down here so I can rip your arm off.<br>
Jumping and swimming are virtually non-existant in FFXI.  Which sounds bad at first, but you don't really need either one of them to get by.  Most of the world is pretty smoothly rendered, unlike the jerky EQ terrain, making jumping unnecessary.  If you can't go over something, it's usually really obvious how to go around it.  There don't seem to be any places where swimming would be useful, either.  Jump does make a notable appearance in the game, however, as a special attack of the Dragoon.  Using Jump, a Dragoon can leap out of attack range of a monster for a few rounds, then come racing down like the wrath of god upon your enemy's head.  This is really cool to see in action, especially Taru Dragoons, just don't plan on attacking the ground to get over that next hill.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zerlatikflaimweaver>Zerlatik Flaimweaver</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Channeler</span><br>  Posts: 231<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/22/03 7:45 pm)</font><br>     <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: and the info bomb goes MASSIVE....</span><hr size=1> &lt;Edit&gt; Part 2/4.  Hah, found a way around the HTML ban.  Darn you, Ezboard.  Darn you to Heck!<br>
<br>
(6) Spooooooooon!<br>
Remember earlier where I said the guild system was different than EQ?  Well, there are actual guilds in FFXI.  Unlike EQ these guilds aren't for learning jobs or socializing with whatever freakish family members your guildmates have dragged along to the party.  Nope, FFXI guilds are like tradeskill havens.  Each guild specializes in a particular craft, from Bonecrafters and Tailors to Culinarians and Blacksmiths.  Advancing within each guild is also very desirable, as the higher your guild ranking, the less likely you are to blow a recipe and the less restrictions you have on what you can craft.  As you level, your guild will give out quests to improve your ranking.  Some randomness is also involved in the crafting process, such that higher ranked players will have a chance to create exceptional items when attempting a recipe.<br>
<br>
