<br>
Why would someone choose this over NWN, Morrowind, or say, FFXII? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=goladus>Goladus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<br>Err, Forum Arch Mage?</span><br>  Posts: 4861<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/23/03 3:31 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: An EQ player's take on Final Fantasy XI (Info Bomb).</span><hr size=1> I also have a question.  How is the sound and music?<br>
<br>
Recently EQ music has gotten better, and in many instances EQ sounds were incredibly helpful and lifelike.  But in general music in EQ seems like just something to add to the ambiance, and sound effects are intended to be realistic.<br>
<br>
Music in Final Fantasy has traditionally played a far more active role in the game, significantly influencing the way one percieve characters, settings, and situations.  Sound effects tend to be imaginative and stylized.  I'm curious if you can tell whether this F.F. continues these traditions. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=verylowsodium>VERY LOW SODIUM</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 102<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/23/03 7:10 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: An EQ player's take on Final Fantasy XI (Info Bomb).</span><hr size=1> Just not Final Fantasy without the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.students.sonoma.edu/users/w/walz/ffmidi/FF1prelu.mid">Prelude</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. Just downloaded the opening song.. it's there<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :grin --><img src=http://www.graffe.com/emoticons/leetgrin.gif ALT=":grin"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <p>&quot;But I think you'll need to concede my basic point, which is that it is impossible for you to have an antimatter burrito. Especially with current technology.&quot;</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=verylowsodium>VERY LOW SODIUM</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.thegeekhost.com/thoughtlover/pic/edhappy.gif" BORDER=0> at: 6/23/03 7:17 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=goladus>Goladus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<br>Err, Forum Arch Mage?</span><br>  Posts: 4864<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/23/03 9:24 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: An EQ player's take on Final Fantasy XI (Info Bomb).</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>It sounds pretty cool, but... It also seems like something I would rather play single-player...<br>
<br>
Why would someone choose this over NWN, Morrowind, or say, FFXII? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Before I answer this, would you be able to elaborate a little bit more on both points?<br>
<br>
What seems too single-player oriented about this game, and how are NWN and Morrowind better? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zerlatikflaimweaver>Zerlatik Flaimweaver</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Channeler</span><br>  Posts: 237<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/23/03 2:15 pm)</font><br>     <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: An EQ player's take on Final Fantasy XI (Info Bomb).</span><hr size=1> &lt;Edit&gt; What do you know, turns out the HTML filter just didn't like the way I was doing arrows.  It's always something mind-numbingly stupid with Ezboard, isn't it?<br>
<br>
(7) I'm with Stupid ====&gt;<br>
Faction within FFXI is more important than in other MMORPGs.  It actually has a point beyond whether or not that guard is going to welcome or attack you.  There are three basic factions: Republic of Bastok, Kingdom of San'Doria, and Federation of Windurst.  Each faction is chosen upon startup, and you're rewarded for choosing your racial faction with a special stat ring.  All factions have strong and weak points.  Windurst is the starting faction of the Tarus and Mithras, for instance, and they rock at crafting magic items.  Bastok is the hume and gralkas, and tends toward heavy industry, this faction has guns.  San'Doria is the elvaan homeland, and they specialize in swords and armor of all types.  Another important aspect of faction has to do with loot.  At the end of every week, conquest points for each faction are calculated.  If your faction has enough of them, you gain control of new areas of the world.  Fighting in a region your faction controls is very rewarding.  For one thing, you get guards.  Guards can save your butt, or buff you with special effects to improve your loot gathering abilities.  As PvP is currently unimplemented in FFXI, it's up to you to outperform other factions, rather than conquering them the old fashioned way.<br>
<br>
(a) Whatsa matter, Colonel Sanders?  CHICKEN?!?<br>
Rank within your faction has a point.  It directly effects how NPCs from that faction perceive you.  To improve your rank you have to do missions for that faction.  These differ from quests in that they're more covert in nature, and you can't repeat them.  You will know what rank you are within a faction most of the time.  Upon completion of the required quests, a giant message is displayed on the screen announcing a rank improvement.  Also, you have a bar near your stats that tells you how liked by your faction you are.  <br>
<br>
(b) I claim this land for Spain!<br>
To help explain rank and faction a little better, lets examine probably the best buff in the game, Signet.  Signet is recieved from any guard of your faction before you head into hostile territory.  Signet will last an extra hour for every rank you have within the faction.  What Signet does is increase your chances to gain crystals (the magic McGuffins of FFXI), and allows you to accrue conquest points.  Conquest points are what gets tallied for zone control at the end of the week.  You can also spend conquest points on special items as you advance in ranks.  Spent conquest points still count toward your faction's totals.  Conquest points may also open up new areas to shop or activate new quests.  Faction members generally like it when you help their cause.  Wander out without a signet buff, and you might as well not be fighting in that area as far as your faction is concerned.<br>
<br>
(c) We're on a mission from God.<br>
Missions are structured to be easily completed by players at or around those levels where you'd need to have the next faction rank. They start out really easy, and end up being pretty drawn out affairs.  Each faction has a different set of missions for it's players, however by about the 9th mission, they start to blur together to the point where the only major difference is who you have to report to in each stage.  Mission goals are almost invariably triggered as well, no more waiting around unless the mission specifically requires you to.<br>
<br>
(d) Hey, beautiful woman!  We don't take kindly to your type round here.<br>
While you want to advance your own rank, it behooves you to occasionally group with players of other factions.  The biggest reason for this is that quests and missions occasionally require you to visit other cities, and it's always nice if the guards have a reason to let you in.  Opposing guards, while not hostile enough to kill you, aren't really inclined to help out your sorry butt if something clamps down on it, either.  For this reason, you will occasionally want to group with members of other factions.  Just not too many of them, as you're not in it to gain their faction more conquest points.  <br>
<br>
8. Just Jack! /em waves hands near his face.<br>
Fame is another important factor in your success.  Fame differs from rank in that while Rank involves how much power you may wield, fame is how well known you are in the world at large.  Think of it this way: The Undersecretary for Defense is a pretty dang powerful man, but I couldn't name him if you paid me.  On the other hand, David Lee Roth is lucky if the checkout girl respects him, but most of us could pick him out of a lineup.  Fame is gained by questing.  Quests are given out in a similar fashion to EQ, you wander around and accost NPCs until they give you something to do.  Thankfully, unlike EQ, both missions and quests don't involve trying to outsmart the game designer by figuring out which questions about an important term will generate responses.  If you have enough fame and rank to ask about something, the menu will prompt you with the correct question.  An NPC who won't tell you jack about a quest at first will gladly cough up his life story for someone of enough fame and rank.  Apparently, you get different levels of fame for every town by doing quests there, whether they're your faction or not.<br>
<br>
Also most quests don't appear to require massive amounts of time and effort, (read giant camp fests).  For instance, I've mentioned the advanced class quests previously.  Now I'd like to mention the AF quests, which are like epic armors for each class.  The Black Mage AF hat quest, for example, involves a final battle with a NM.  Thing is, you don't need a drop from this monster, you just need credit for the kill.  This leads to AF alliances, where multiple Black Mages will party together to trigger the NM, wait for him to despawn, then trigger another one for another mage.  When the final monster for the alliance is triggered, he gets to be the proud recipient of a multi-nuke beatdown.  Everyone then gets credit and heads off to retrieve their armor.  Once they finish, the next alliance is free to head on in and do their battle.  Unlike the frustration many of us saw in Velious or Luclin armor quests, FFXI seems to be relatively peaceful by comparison.  The hardest part is finding the people to help with the quest. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :grin --><img src=http://www.graffe.com/emoticons/leetgrin.gif ALT=":grin"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
9. Dear God, whats this I hear about a story?<br>
Yup, FFXI has a story.  Its surprisingly a good one too.  Unlike EQ, there is no drop in NPC story element either.  Instead of surprise visits from Alkabor and his gang of imbeciles, you have a well structured sequence of missions that lead you along the storyline.  If an NPC is important to the storyline, he or shes in the game already.  Basically, a long time ago the forces of light used crystals to crush the forces of darkness.  After so many years of everything running smoothly, monsters have started appearing on the edges of populated areas.  On top of that, crystals are getting rarer.  So, to combat this, each empire in the old alliance is on a quest to grab as much prime real-estate as possible to help it gather more crystals and keep it from being overrun.  Thats the bare-bones of your backstory.  From there, it takes off in true Final Fantasy style so that you end up understanding every nuance of the story from age to age, and identify every major player in the struggle.  Square-Enix likes to describe the focus on the story by the line: The players = the characters.  This isnt nearly as odd as it sounds.  What it means is that every player in the game is potentially important to moving the story along, and you feel that way as you play.  This game is crawling with cut scenes.  Every quest, every mission, everything has its own special cut scene.  Some have multiple cut scenes.  Acquiring cut scenes is sometimes more important that acquiring quest items.  S-E likes to take out all the stops in this area.  You know when the storyline has advanced, and you almost always gain new information to help make sense out of all of it.  The giant gaps we saw in the EQ storyline are largely absent from FFXI.  Also, the storyline has a definitive beginning and end.  Sure, not everyone is going to want to finish off the Shadow Lord, but the option to do so is there if you want it.  Granted, the game doesnt end when you do it, but Id still love to see the cut scene for that.  Shadow Lord isn't even the last battle, you can go on missions for two more ranks after that.<br>
<br>
10. Playboy bunnies would be proud.<br>
I mentioned crystals before, and how important they are in the storyline.  Well, the true significance of these things cant be understated.  Theyre used in everything.  A copper ingot for a particular quest has a recipe that involves a fire crystal and 4 pieces of ore, for instance.  Crystals come in 8 types, 4 common, 4 rare.  Fire and Earth crystals are pretty easy to find, while wind and darkness crystals might take some looking.  Nearly every combine needs a crystal of the appropriate type.  Which sounds bad, but you dont have to master any skills to finish quests if you dont want to.  Tradeskill items made with crystals are all tradeable, and can be purchased from other players.  Thus, if your talent act really needs that set of crystal drinking goblets, you can acquire them without mastering glassblowing yourself.  Remember the Signet buff from before?  Well, that little gift from your guards drastically increases your drop rates for crystals.  Another buff that the guards can give you is Crysta, which is better for gathering crystals, but at the expense of not giving conquest points for kills, it's also shorter in duration.  Depends on how long you expect to hold a piece of territory, I guess.  If your faction snagged a bit of ground by something you suspect could only have been an act of god, Crysta might be worth it, as it'll revert back next week anyway.  Other skills also help with this area, such as the Thiefs Treasure Hunt ability.  In fact, thief and ranger main/sub jobs are pretty common in groups hunting solely for treasure and crystals.  <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zerlatikflaimweaver>Zerlatik Flaimweaver</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Channeler</span><br>  Posts: 238<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/23/03 2:20 pm)</font><br>     <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: An EQ player's take on Final Fantasy XI (Info Bomb).</span><hr size=1> &lt;Edit&gt; Part 3/3.  Yup, I'm either in the running for a &quot;Resident Novellist&quot; title or the sweet smack of the ban bat.  Either way, when you spend a week writing something, you're going all the way with it.  Incidentally, how's the paint on your house look from the top of this thread?<br>
<br>
11. We are an equal opportunity employer.<br>
Remember how I said that race was fixed, but class is not?  Well, the extent of this is such that any race can choose any class.  Granted, some of you are more suited to specific classes, but if you really want to be a Gralka Black Mage, you can do it.  Taru Dragoons are also very interesting to watch in battle.  Any Taru melee class isnt likely to do a lot of damage, but theres definitely something to be said for sucking with style.  Later on, you can correct a great deal of your racial disadvantages with proper gear upgrades.  You may never reach maximum levels as easily as other races, but you can become reasonably effective if you stay at it long enough.<br>
<br>
12.  Lions and Tigers and GMs, oh my!<br>
Square-Enix has gone out on a limb and stated straight up that there will be 24 hr GM support.  Full GMs, too.  Also, GMs are required to be bilingual, to apply youve gotta be fluent in both English and Japanese.  Not just spoken Japanese either, you need to know two of the three written forms in order to translate, the semi formal and slang styles.  If you cant wrap your head around Hirigana and Katakana, they dont want you.  Which means, youve probably got reasonably intelligent GMs.  Were dealing at least with high school graduates here, and given the requirements placed on them, its probable that they can troubleshoot and problem solve at a higher level than the often simian EQ support.  If you can handle the language, its not a bad job.  Doesnt seem to be inspiring a lot of complaints from the current crop of players, either.<br>
<br>
13.  The Black Mage vs. the wizard.<br>
Well, most of us are concerned with this topic, so I thought Id explore it a little here too.  Black Mages seem to be relatively solid in terms of their role within a party.  I mean, theyre one of the big six.  Everyone in the game knows what they do and has played with one or as one.  They seem to have avoided the shaft of master of arcane teleportation, Ive only found two spells in that line.  Dezone, which I think is an evac, and I believe theres an evac to town as well.  FFXIs spell lists are also pretty intuitive.  For instance, theres Fire 1, which is a fire based nuke spell.  As monsters get more powerful with leveling, you get Fire 2 and 3, which are upgraded versions of this spell.  As you get new spells, you can easily tell what they are and what they do, before you send them down range on the monsters.  I dont know as yet if they have old favorites like Ultima or Meteo, but my fingers are crossed.  Biggest complaint right now about BLMs is that we have too much mana, with Taru BLMs often over nuking during combat to avoid wasting downtime.  Its a welcome change, from my perspective.  Also, those who sub WM for the extra mana are welcomed in parties as a backup healer for the group, so youve got options if the group isnt mage friendly.  Strangely, some players report that BLMs are one of the holy trinity classes in FFXI, apparently it's hard to do without them. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :grinyes --><img src=http://www.graffe.com/emoticons/yes.gif ALT=":grinyes"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
(a) That old black magic...<br>
Higher level BLM spells are quested, similar to higher level wizard spells in EQ.  Some also drop from NMs in high level zones.  Difference is that you know a particular NM is going to drop a certain spell, and you can expect to get it if your the only member of your alliance who needs it.  Popular NMs also lead to many of these spells being auctioned off.  I think right now there are 8 rare BLM spells, with Quake being the rarest, simply because not very many parties kill that particular NM.  I haven't heard anything about the spawn times on these NMs, but I have a lot of hope that they aren't anywhere near as bad as the NTOV/Ssra/Seru/etc runs we've all grown to loathe.  From what I've seen of the quests, they aren't bad.  As I mentioned, no mob waiting on quests, so it's all a matter of finding some buddies.<br>
<br>
14.  For Dmitry. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :dmitry --><img src=http://www.graffe.com/emoticons/dmitry.gif ALT=":dmitry"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Pointy hats.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->  There, Ive said it.  Cats out of the bag.  BLMs get pointy hats.  RMs get pointy cowboy hats, with pimp feathers.  Ive seen the screenshots.  The Taru at least get them.  Theyre big, tan, have just the right amount of curvature at the top, and ooze style.  If pointy hats are your cup of tea, this is definitely your game.  Remember kiddies, theres nuking, and then theres nuking with style.<br>
<br>
15. Buy my crap.<br>
Can't remember if I've mentioned this yet, but auction has been tweaked with FFXI as well.  For instance, you don't have to be physically present to sell something.  You hit the auction zone/house?, tell the barker how much to charge, hand over the item, and go about your business.  Later on, you get paid for it.  It's so clean and simple it almost brings tears to my eyes.<br>
<br>
Anyway, thats my two cp.  On a lot of fronts, it looks better than EQ, at least in terms of the experience I was expecting in EQ and found lacking.  There are other ways that it probably wont live up to expectations.  For instance, the Link Shell system seems kind of a pale comparison to EQs guild management system.  However, I should mention that alliances seem to be maxxed for 18 people, which means most encounters are tuned to pretty small sized shell networks.   Itd also be nice if Chocos were a little easier to obtain/handle.  Whats up with having to get boat/airship rides?  I don't like the server selection system, not because I think it goes too far, but because I don't think it goes far enough.  I mean, if you were randomly put on a server every time you logged on, you'd have less trouble with uber guilds owning a server, or server economies being radically screwed over on some servers and virtually non-existant on others.  But, other than those, Im not finding a lot to pick at.  Well have to see how it pans out after NA release, if it lets me down, Ill be back.  <br>
<br>
I welcome your thoughts and comments.  My view's more than a little biased, so I'd appreciate someone coming along to poke some holes in it about now.  Also, could any of S-E ideas be workable in EQ to address some of the probs we've experienced?<br>
<br>
More information can be found at the following sites if youre interested:<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.ffxionline.com" target="top">www.ffxionline.com</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.playonline.com/ff11us/index.shtml" target="top">FFXI Official NA Launch Site (Run by Square-Enix)</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.ffinsider.net/ff11/" target="top">Final Fantasy Insider's coverage of FFXI</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
 <p><center><b><u>The Man's Prayer</u></b><BR>
<center>I'm a man<BR>
<center>But I can change<BR>
<center>If I have to<BR>
